  "summary": "Inspector Huishe informs Dr. Arthur Calgary that Mr. Darlant, a disabled man with polio, is conducting his own detective work regarding a murder case at the Sunset Corner. Huishe notes that while Darlant is smart and intuitive, he will likely keep his findings to himself. Calgary expresses concern that the involved parties must be informed of the truth, but Huishe suggests they may already know.\n\nCalgary later visits Molly Craig. Molly discusses rumors surrounding a murder case involving a man named Joe, who was pardoned after claiming innocence. She speculates that the other brother, Mickey, might be responsible, noting his unpredictable nature and his potential plan to escape to Persia. Molly also mentions rumors that a husband and secretary were involved, suggesting a husband might use poison.\n\nCalgary then meets with a middle-aged woman to gather information for a book he intends to write regarding pathological personalities. He uses his experience with the Hayes-Bentley Expedition to Antarctica to build rapport with her. The woman discusses her relationship with Jacquie, whom she describes as charming but potentially motivated by money. She expresses a willingness to do anything for him, despite his death, and mentions plans they had to travel to France or Italy if his schemes succeeded.\n\nIn a separate scene, Philip Durrant wakes up feeling refreshed and anticipates a visit from Tina. His wife, Mary (Polly), informs him that Hester is coming home. This prompts a brief tension between the couple, as Philip dismisses Mary's implication that he has inappropriate feelings for Tina.",
